<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8"/>
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"/>
<title>Sector Momentum — Sentiment</title>
<link rel="alternate" type="application/atom+xml" title="Sector Momentum Feed" href="feed.xml"/>
<script src="{{ plotly_bundle }}"></script>
<style>
{% include "_style.html.j2" %}
</style>
</head>
<body>

{#- FinBERT news-sentiment table (sectors only). -#}
{% macro sentiment_table(rows) %}
<div style="overflow-x:auto">
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th data-i18n="sent_col_sector">Sector</th>
        <th data-i18n="sent_col_region">Region</th>
        <th data-i18n="sent_col_news_polarity">Polarity</th>
        <th data-i18n="sent_col_news_count">Articles</th>
        <th data-i18n="sent_col_news_pos">Pos%</th>
        <th data-i18n="sent_col_news_neg">Neg%</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      {% for r in rows %}
      <tr>
        <td>{{ r.sector }}</td>
        <td>{{ r.region }}</td>
        <td class="{% if r.news_polarity != '—' %}{% if r.news_polarity.startswith('+') %}signal-hi{% elif r.news_polarity.startswith('-') %}signal-lo{% endif %}{% endif %}">{{ r.news_polarity }}</td>
        <td>{{ r.news_count }}</td>
        <td>{{ r.news_positive_pct }}</td>
        <td>{{ r.news_negative_pct }}</td>
      </tr>
      {% endfor %}
    </tbody>
  </table>
</div>
{% endmacro %}

{#- Scatter footnote. -#}
{% macro scatter_footnote() %}
<p style="color:var(--fg4);font-size:0.8rem;padding:8px 0 0 4px" data-i18n-html="sentiment_footnote">
  Bottom-right quadrant (data ahead of sentiment) is the early-rotation zone.
  Hollow points = no news sentiment this scan (source unavailable).
  Sentiment is a confirming signal — noisy and news-driven.
  This is analytical tooling, not investment advice.
</p>
{% endmacro %}

<!-- Header -->
{% set active_segment = "sentiment" %}
{% include '_header.html.j2' %}

<div class="card">
<section class="tab-panel active">
  <p class="tab-note" data-i18n="note_sentiment">Sentiment weighting affects the leaderboard ranking only.</p>

  <div class="utility-row">
  <details class="tab-guide">
    <summary data-i18n="guide_summary_sentiment">How is the sentiment score calculated?</summary>
    <div class="tab-guide-body" data-i18n-html="guide_body_sentiment">
      <h4>Source — FinBERT news sentiment</h4>
      <p>The <strong>sentiment score</strong> is built from recent financial
         news. For each of the 11 GICS sectors we fetch the latest 24&nbsp;hours
         of English-language headlines from the <strong>GDELT</strong> global
         news index (up to 250 per sector, matched via sector-specific topic
         codes). Each headline is scored by <strong>ProsusAI/finbert</strong>, a
         finance-tuned BERT model that classifies text as positive, negative or
         neutral with a confidence score. The per-sector <em>mean signed
         polarity</em> (positive&nbsp;=&nbsp;+score,
         negative&nbsp;=&nbsp;&minus;score, neutral&nbsp;=&nbsp;0) is then
         z-scored across the 11 sectors:
         <span class="signal-hi">positive = more bullish news vs peers</span>,
         <span class="signal-lo">negative = more bearish</span>.
         Both US and EU rows for the same GICS sector share the same score —
         financial news sentiment is global. If FinBERT or GDELT is unavailable,
         the score is left blank for that scan.</p>
      <h4>Table columns</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Polarity</strong> — mean signed sentiment from recent news
            headlines. Green = bullish, red = bearish.</li>
        <li><strong>Articles</strong> — number of headlines scored.</li>
        <li><strong>Pos%</strong> — fraction classified as positive.</li>
        <li><strong>Neg%</strong> — fraction classified as negative.</li>
      </ul>
      <h4>It does not drive the ranking by default</h4>
      <p>The leaderboard composite is built from price/momentum signals only.
         Sentiment changes the ranking <em>only</em> when you enable the
         <strong>Sentiment toggle</strong>, at the weight you choose. Treat it as
         a confirmer, not a driver — news sentiment is noisy and can lag price.</p>
    </div>
  </details>
  </div>

  <div class="chart-container" id="sentiment-scatter" style="height:560px"></div>
  {{ scatter_footnote() }}
  {% if sentiment_signal_rows %}
  <h3 style="margin:24px 0 8px 4px" data-i18n="sent_news_heading">News sentiment</h3>
  {{ sentiment_table(sentiment_signal_rows) }}
  {% endif %}
</section>
</div>

<script>
var SENTIMENT_DATA = {{ sentiment_scatter_json | js_json }};

// Plot the scatter once the container is laid out.
(function () {
  if (!window.Plotly) return;
  var el = document.getElementById('sentiment-scatter');
  if (!el) return;
  Plotly.newPlot(el, SENTIMENT_DATA.data, SENTIMENT_DATA.layout, {responsive: true});
})();

{% include "_i18n.html.j2" %}
</script>

{% include '_footer.html.j2' %}

</body>
</html>
